■ Kernels & Gram Matrix¶

Let's start by defining different kernels that we will be using in this work:

In [2]:
def linear_kernel(a, b):
    """linear kernel"""
    return np.inner(a, b)

def polynomial_kernel(a, b, c, d):
    """Polynomial kernel"""
    return (np.inner(a, b) + c) ** d

def gaussian_kernel(a, b, gamma):
    """Gaussian kernel"""
    return np.exp(-.5 * np.linalg.norm((a - b)**2) / gamma)

def laplace_kernel(a, b):
    """Laplce kernel"""
    return np.exp(-np.linalg.norm(a - b, ord=1))

def exponential_kernel(a, b):
    """Exponential kernel"""
    return np.exp(np.inner(a, b))

def gram_matrix(X, kernel, gamma=None):
    """returns Gram matrix of X using the given kernel"""
    n, _ = X.shape
    K = np.array([kernel(X[i], X[j], gamma=gamma) 
                  for i in range(n)
                  for j in range(n)]).reshape(n, n)
    return K

■ 3. Kernel PCA (↑)¶

In this last section, we will apply Kernel PCA to our dataset, by using both Polynomial & Gaussian kernels.

3.1. Polynomial Kernel¶

In [8]:
## create & fit KPCA
gamma = 5
degree = 13
kernel = 'poly'
KPCA = KernelPCA(n_components=2, gamma=gamma, degree=degree, kernel=kernel)
X_kpca = KPCA.fit_transform(X)


## display transformed data
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=4, figsize=(18, 12))
axes = axes.flatten()

gammas = range(1, 13)
for e, gamma in enumerate(gammas):
    KPCA = KernelPCA(n_components=2, gamma=gamma, degree=degree, kernel=kernel)
    X_kpca = KPCA.fit_transform(X)
    axes[e].scatter(X_kpca[:, 0], X_kpca[:, 1], c=y, cmap='winter')
    axes[e].set_title(r'gamma($\gamma$)=' + str(gamma))

plt.show()

Comment: polynomial kernel does not seem to be suited for such cases, even with higher polynomial degrees.

3.2. Gaussian Kernel¶

In [9]:
## create & fit KPCA
gamma = 10
kernel = 'rbf'
KPCA = KernelPCA(n_components=2, gamma=gamma, kernel=kernel)
X_kpca = KPCA.fit_transform(X)


## display transformed data
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=4, figsize=(18, 12))
axes = axes.flatten()

gammas = range(1, 13)
for e, gamma in enumerate(gammas):
    KPCA = KernelPCA(n_components=2, gamma=gamma, kernel='rbf')
    X_kpca = KPCA.fit_transform(X)
    axes[e].scatter(X_kpca[:, 0], X_kpca[:, 1], c=y, cmap='winter')
    axes[e].set_title(r'gamma($\gamma$)=' + str(gamma))

plt.show()

Comments:

  • Unlike polynomial kernel, the Gaussian one seem to work well.
  • There is a range of values of bindwidth that makes things work perfectly, but beyond a given value (in our case $\gamma=9$) it fails to linearly separate the two classes.

3.3. spectrum¶

  • $\hat{\Sigma}=\dfrac1n\sum_{i}k_{x_i}\otimes k_{x_i}=\dfrac1n\sum_{i}X_iX_i^T=\frac{X^TX}{n}$
  • $K_n = \frac{XX^T}{n} = \left\{\frac{X_i^TX_j}{n}\right\}_{i, j}$
  • The non-zero eignevalues of $\hat{\Sigma}$ are exactly the same as the gram matrix: $$Sp(K_n) = Sp(\hat{\Sigma})$$
In [10]:
## compute gram matrix with gaissian kernel
gamma = .5
kenrel = gaussian_kernel
K = gram_matrix(X, kenrel, gamma=gamma)

## the normalized Gram matrix
Kn = K / n_samples

## compute the eigenvalues of the gram matrix
eigv, _ = np.linalg.eig(Kn)

## display eigenvalues
plt.plot(eigv)
plt.xlabel('i')
plt.ylabel('eigenvalue')
plt.show()
In [11]:
## the number of eigen values
n_eigv = len(eigv)

print(f'number of eigenvalues: {n_eigv}')

## compute the non-zero eigenvalues
non_zero_eigv = np.sum(eigv > 10e-5)

print(f'number of non-zero eigenvalues: {non_zero_eigv}')

number of eigenvalues: 1000

Comment: $$\normalsize\gamma \uparrow \leadsto \|u\|_o \downarrow \text{ sparsity}$$
